ce:section.ce:para:
The electrostatic self-assembly strategy has been attracted substantial attention due to the versatility of readily tailoring the size, composition, porosity, stability, and surface functionality of the resulting hybrid nanocomposite by incorporating multiple functionalities using a facile, convenience and inexpensive process as a novel method [22]. For example, Ong et al. [11] reported the fabrication of GO and proton-functionalized g-C3N4 using the electrostatic self-assembly strategy obtained a new photocatalyst and exhibited the high efficiency of methane evolution. Xu et al. [13] fabricated the CNT/g-C3N4 nanocomposite via the electrostatic self-assembly strategy at room temperature. In this study, we design and synthesis a composite material based on g-C3N4 integrated with CQDs at room temperature and atmospheric pressure through the electrostatic self-assembly strategy. We demonstrated an ingenious design to prepare the protonated g-C3N4 (HpCN) by using the concentrated HNO3-refluxed g-C3N4. The obtained HpCN used to modify pure g-C3N4 possesses positive polarity (Fig. 2). The surface of CQDs exhibited negative polarity similar to that of GO and CNTCOO− 
                     [23]. Thus, CQDs and HpCN are successfully coupled together owing to the strong and mutual electrostatic repulsion during dispersion (Fig. 1

                     ).

Through the EIS analysis, excellent electronic conductivity of the CQDs/HpCN nanocomposite modified electrode consequence was obtained. In particular, the high conductivity CQDs played an important role in attaining an efficient pathway for electron transport that can fundamentally address the poor electronic conductivity of HpCN and allow fast charge separation and collection (Fig. 9
                        ). To further investigate the photocatalystical activity of the CQDs/HpCN hybrid further, the transient photocurrent responses of g-C3N4, HpCN and CQDs/HpCN used as photoelectrodes for solar electricity production were tested by on–off cycles of irradiation. The photocurrent density obtained by using the CQDs/HpCN modified photoelectrode was 1.89μAcm−2 (in Fig. 9), which was much larger than the photocurrent density of pure g-C3N4 (0.73μAcm−2) and HpCN (1.14μAcm−2). The efficiency of photocurrent generation was increased because of the synergetic effect of HpCN and CQDs semiconductor. We also investigated the photocatalytic activity of the samples by evaluating the degradation of MB solution under visible light irradiation. Notably, the concentrations of MB decreased rapidly when CQDs/HpCN was applied, and was sufficiently stable during the repeated experiments without significant loss of photocatalytic performance (see Fig. 10
                        ).
